Abstract data types for Earth observation

Choose view:

Description

Example phenomena relevant to Earth observation in a 3D space. Here, the three axes space, time, and theme provide an ordering principle for EO spatio-temporal phenomena. Note that aspect space can be conceived as position (0-dimensional, coordinate tupel or tripel), or as geometric features (set of coordinate tupels, e.g. size, compactness, etc.).
We suggest the following abstract data types in the context of EO data cubes, which are illustrated above:
  • Coverage: A coverage is constructed by fixing time, manipulating position, observing theme (continuous or discrete).
  • Composition: A composition is constructed by fixing time, manipulating theme, observing space.
  • Time series: A time series is constructed by fixing the position, manipulating time, observing theme (continuous or discrete).
  • Trajectory: A trajectory is constructed by fixing theme, manipulating time, observing position.
  • Evolution: An evolution is constructed by fixing theme, manipulating time, observing space.
To describe more complex phenomena, the abstract data types can be combined. For example, a pixel-based land cover change map might be constructed as a coverage of time series. For an object-based grouping of the change classes, a composition of coverage of time series allows object-based evaluation. Another example is an object-based crop cycle, where potential changes of size and shape of a specific agricultural field might be expressed by a evolution of time series.

Usage

Use right mouse button to zoom-in and zoom-out. Use left mouse button to rotate the view. Klick with the middle mouse button moves the view. If you are lost, reload the page to go back to the initial view.
